00:30:41.630 --> 00:30:43.520
Oh no.

00:30:43.520 --> 00:30:44.710
There you go.

00:30:44.710 --> 00:30:45.548
OK.

00:30:45.548 --> 00:30:46.964
OK now who's that
smart pants one?

00:30:46.964 --> 00:30:48.751
This guy.

00:30:48.751 --> 00:30:49.250
OK.

00:30:49.250 --> 00:30:51.708
So these are just some of those
kids from the slide before,

00:30:51.708 --> 00:30:54.760
and again I guess from the
performers perspective,

00:30:54.760 --> 00:30:56.230
you're like oh, there's only 5.

00:30:56.230 --> 00:30:58.150
But then you see all
the kids laughing

00:30:58.150 --> 00:31:01.900
and it immediately
becomes totally worth it.

00:31:01.900 --> 00:31:06.490
And this is in Haiti,
this is like about a month

00:31:06.490 --> 00:31:08.037
after the earthquake.

00:31:08.037 --> 00:31:08.870
This is David again.

00:31:08.870 --> 00:31:12.100
I've been on a few trips with
David, because I like David.

00:31:12.100 --> 00:31:15.630
And the kids are
just super happy,

00:31:15.630 --> 00:31:19.880
and just bringing smiles to
their faces is wonderful.

00:31:19.880 --> 00:31:21.890
And we were also
really surprised

00:31:21.890 --> 00:31:24.120
at how quickly we
were asked to come

00:31:24.120 --> 00:31:26.609
to Haiti after the
earthquake, because there's

00:31:26.609 --> 00:31:28.400
kind of the first
responders, and obviously

00:31:28.400 --> 00:31:29.858
that takes priority,
and that's why

00:31:29.858 --> 00:31:31.490
we wait until we're
asked to come.

00:31:31.490 --> 00:31:35.592
But then there were
we had the experience

00:31:35.592 --> 00:31:36.800
over and over and over again.

00:31:36.800 --> 00:31:39.870
We were going to these kind
of makeshift hospital areas,

00:31:39.870 --> 00:31:43.320
and a lot of the
doctors and nurses

00:31:43.320 --> 00:31:46.110
who were there,
who had been there

00:31:46.110 --> 00:31:49.290
since the earthquake or a few
days after, we saying this

00:31:49.290 --> 00:31:51.430
is the first time
we've seen anyone smile

00:31:51.430 --> 00:31:54.740
in a month and a half
or whatever it was.

00:31:54.740 --> 00:31:58.540
And so I think that is why we're
asked often too come places.

00:31:58.540 --> 00:32:00.240
So that's sort of
an acute situation.

00:32:00.240 --> 00:32:02.560
But the example is just
that sometimes there

00:32:02.560 --> 00:32:05.344
is that need to sort
of shake things up.

00:32:05.344 --> 00:32:07.260
And I think that laughter
can be very healing,

00:32:07.260 --> 00:32:10.230
and that's part of the healing
process and part of connecting.

00:32:10.230 --> 00:32:13.160
And so going after
the earthquake

00:32:13.160 --> 00:32:16.420
was definitely in an
intense experience,

00:32:16.420 --> 00:32:18.150
but we were so well received.

00:32:18.150 --> 00:32:25.970
And there was a
little girl who--

00:32:25.970 --> 00:32:29.570
I guess she was found next
to her mom, who have passed.

00:32:29.570 --> 00:32:33.180
And had sort of become
mute from the situation.

00:32:33.180 --> 00:32:35.389
And we played with her, and
sort of got her to laugh,

00:32:35.389 --> 00:32:36.763
and the nurses
like reported back

00:32:36.763 --> 00:32:38.020
that then she started talking.

00:32:38.020 --> 00:32:40.559
So OK, that's like
a beautiful story.

00:32:40.559 --> 00:32:42.100
Doesn't always happen
that way, but I

00:32:42.100 --> 00:32:44.210
think that it kind
of illustrates

00:32:44.210 --> 00:32:46.530
that that's the kind of
thing that we can do just

00:32:46.530 --> 00:32:48.820
through play.

00:32:48.820 --> 00:32:49.740
And we have the time.

00:32:49.740 --> 00:32:54.000
We go and sort of make time
for that sort of thing.

00:32:54.000 --> 00:33:02.780
And so this is also soon
after that same trip.

00:33:02.780 --> 00:33:08.720
And just working closely
with the doctors and nurses,

00:33:08.720 --> 00:33:13.560
and we went often like from tent
to tent, or from sort of site

00:33:13.560 --> 00:33:17.610
to site, and put on shows for
just like a handful of people

00:33:17.610 --> 00:33:19.590
and sometimes for people
who had been waiting

00:33:19.590 --> 00:33:22.550
for medical care
for a few weeks,

00:33:22.550 --> 00:33:25.360
and just sort of camped out
waiting for medical care.

00:33:25.360 --> 00:33:26.770
And those were bigger shows.

00:33:26.770 --> 00:33:28.016
We had a show.

00:33:28.016 --> 00:33:29.890
This is sort of an
awkward experience we had.

00:33:29.890 --> 00:33:31.450
They were like oh there
is all this space.

00:33:31.450 --> 00:33:32.158
That's fantastic.

00:33:32.158 --> 00:33:33.710
Because sometimes
that's an issue,

00:33:33.710 --> 00:33:35.043
especially after the earthquake.

00:33:35.043 --> 00:33:37.176
There wasn't always space.

00:33:37.176 --> 00:33:38.300
And so we found this space.

00:33:38.300 --> 00:33:40.020
We're like, oh great, it's
some sort of hospital setting.

00:33:40.020 --> 00:33:40.679
Fantastic.

00:33:40.679 --> 00:33:42.720
So we like set up the
show, we're doing the show,

00:33:42.720 --> 00:33:45.420
everything's going great,
and in the middle of the show

00:33:45.420 --> 00:33:47.619
we hear like Doctor Chang
come here immediately!

00:33:47.619 --> 00:33:48.910
And we're like what's going on?

00:33:48.910 --> 00:33:51.560
And like someone's like rolled
through the middle of our show.

00:33:51.560 --> 00:33:54.880
And we're like, Oh, we're in
front of the operating room.

00:33:54.880 --> 00:33:57.660
That's why the space is clear.

00:33:57.660 --> 00:34:01.210
But everyone was
like ha, ha, ha.

00:34:01.210 --> 00:34:04.440
We were clearly back then
like oh no, we didn't know.

00:34:04.440 --> 00:34:07.330
But it worked out.

00:34:07.330 --> 00:34:14.909
OK, so this is from the most
recent trip to Palestine.

00:34:14.909 --> 00:34:19.699
And for me, this is just about
how situations can be complex,

00:34:19.699 --> 00:34:21.730
to say the least.

00:34:21.730 --> 00:34:28.040
And this is in a refugee camp,
and these are not real guns,

00:34:28.040 --> 00:34:29.230
these are toy guns.

00:34:29.230 --> 00:34:32.310
But many of them have a
laser pointer on them.

00:34:32.310 --> 00:34:39.480
And sometimes during the shows,
we'd be like, funny skit,

00:34:39.480 --> 00:34:42.310
and they'd look down and be
like oh, a laser's on me.

00:34:42.310 --> 00:34:45.040
That's uncomfortable.

00:34:45.040 --> 00:34:46.960
So they just had
little like pellets.

00:34:46.960 --> 00:34:48.030
You know?

00:34:48.030 --> 00:34:51.290
So they're not entitled to kill.

00:34:51.290 --> 00:34:54.210
So I tried to like collect
them before the show,

00:34:54.210 --> 00:34:56.590
because I thought like I'll
just feel better about this,

00:34:56.590 --> 00:34:58.770
and maybe I'll be funnier
if I'm not thinking

00:34:58.770 --> 00:35:00.384
about this in the
back of my mind.

00:35:00.384 --> 00:35:02.300
And I took this picture
just because I kind of

00:35:02.300 --> 00:35:04.770
thought like this sort of
exemplifies what's happening.

00:35:06.834 --> 00:35:08.500
But I mean it was
useless, because there

00:35:08.500 --> 00:35:09.480
was like way more of them.

00:35:09.480 --> 00:35:11.320
It was like the most fruitless
thing I've ever tried to do.

00:35:11.320 --> 00:35:12.730
It was like give
me your gun, and we

00:35:12.730 --> 00:35:14.480
don't speak the same
language, that thing.

00:35:14.480 --> 00:35:17.760
Instead they'd be like,
BING, and I'd get shot.

00:35:17.760 --> 00:35:22.670
But these are the kids
that those little play

00:35:22.670 --> 00:35:23.860
guys belong to.

00:35:23.860 --> 00:35:26.450
So they were having
a great time,

00:35:26.450 --> 00:35:28.670
and then we gave them
their toys afterwards.

00:35:28.670 --> 00:35:30.910
So I suppose we could go
into like what that means,

00:35:30.910 --> 00:35:33.580
but I'll leave that for now.

00:35:33.580 --> 00:35:35.630
And just say that what
was really important

00:35:35.630 --> 00:35:38.740
is like having sort of the
connection and the laughter.

00:35:41.560 --> 00:35:45.150
And just allowing
kids to be kids,

00:35:45.150 --> 00:35:48.230
and allowing the space
for that to happen.

00:35:48.230 --> 00:35:54.901
This is a picture of child
soldiers, right, in Sudan.

00:35:54.901 --> 00:36:01.170
And so, this is just kids
being kids, having a good time.

00:36:01.170 --> 00:36:03.940
And this is back in Palestine.

00:36:03.940 --> 00:36:06.840
Some kids stole my
nose, I mean I let them.

00:36:06.840 --> 00:36:11.050
And they were playing
with it, collecting water.

00:36:11.050 --> 00:36:14.000
And then this is in Haiti.

00:36:14.000 --> 00:36:16.520
And this is before
the earthquake.

00:36:16.520 --> 00:36:20.440
And this was a kid who had
like a limp for something.

00:36:23.290 --> 00:36:26.370
It's like an area
set up for boys only.

00:36:26.370 --> 00:36:31.950
It's basically like
a big cement room.

00:36:31.950 --> 00:36:34.450
But it was a place for
kids to go, for these boys

00:36:34.450 --> 00:36:36.660
to go during the day.

00:36:36.660 --> 00:36:39.320
And he was being made fun
of a little bit, I think,

00:36:39.320 --> 00:36:44.271
just because he had
some physical ailments.

00:36:44.271 --> 00:36:45.770
So we sort of pulled
him in and made

00:36:45.770 --> 00:36:48.637
him the star of the show
for this little bit.

00:36:48.637 --> 00:36:50.970
And afterwards, everyone was
like giving him high fives,

00:36:50.970 --> 00:36:52.310
like Yeah!

00:36:52.310 --> 00:36:55.790
So that was sort of
really nice experience.

00:36:55.790 --> 00:37:01.230
David spins a ball in his finger
and gives it over to the kid.

00:37:01.230 --> 00:37:03.782
And we went and so this
place is a really nice place,

00:37:03.782 --> 00:37:05.240
that you didn't
have very-- I mean,

00:37:05.240 --> 00:37:08.250
it was really just a
room in the outdoors.

00:37:08.250 --> 00:37:13.635
But sort of enclosed from the
rest of the outside world,

00:37:13.635 --> 00:37:14.510
I guess a little bit.

00:37:14.510 --> 00:37:16.140
That's a nice safe space.

00:37:16.140 --> 00:37:18.380
But unfortunately this place
was destroyed just right

00:37:18.380 --> 00:37:22.830
after the earthquake which was
sad and hard to go back and see

00:37:22.830 --> 00:37:25.600
that.

00:37:25.600 --> 00:37:28.747
And that's all.

00:37:28.747 --> 00:37:30.830
We're just here to tell
you that we need your help

00:37:30.830 --> 00:37:35.150
kind of spreading awareness
about the organization.

00:37:35.150 --> 00:37:39.020
And this is who we are!

00:37:39.020 --> 00:37:41.285
Clowns Without Borders.

00:37:41.285 --> 00:37:42.410
Do you guys have questions?

00:37:51.164 --> 00:37:52.080
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:38:29.610 --> 00:38:31.860
Is it just you see that more?

00:38:31.860 --> 00:38:36.840
LEAH: I think it's like sort of
from just experiencing clowning

00:38:36.840 --> 00:38:39.670
and performing, like you kind
of learn like who to go to.

00:38:39.670 --> 00:38:43.110
And I mean, mistakes are
made, like that's the truth.

00:38:43.110 --> 00:38:45.955
But I think that
sort of the more

00:38:45.955 --> 00:38:47.580
that you do it, you
kind of figure out,

00:38:47.580 --> 00:38:48.830
OK this is like a good choice.

00:38:48.830 --> 00:38:50.520
I can see from their
facial expression,

00:38:50.520 --> 00:38:52.270
and sort of from the
way they're reacting.

00:38:52.270 --> 00:38:55.275
I mean, on our trips,
more often than not,

00:38:55.275 --> 00:38:56.650
we have like
everyone wanting you

00:38:56.650 --> 00:38:58.149
know, like kind of
the first things.

00:38:58.149 --> 00:38:59.880
I want to be up there, too.

00:38:59.880 --> 00:39:02.710
Like choose me, choose me.

00:39:02.710 --> 00:39:05.470
But I think that's more
of our problem, which

00:39:05.470 --> 00:39:06.740
I think is a good thing.

00:39:06.740 --> 00:39:09.970
It's like we can't bring all the
kids up, but cest la vie, life

00:39:09.970 --> 00:39:11.640
isn't fair.

00:39:11.640 --> 00:39:15.710
But we do sometimes
a dance I've done,

00:39:15.710 --> 00:39:17.210
that like it's kind
of a dance skit.

00:39:17.210 --> 00:39:20.405
And we get like a
man and woman up.

00:39:20.405 --> 00:39:22.880
So sort of like, we usually
get like the caretakers

00:39:22.880 --> 00:39:23.560
of the kids.

00:39:23.560 --> 00:39:26.134
And sometimes they're
a little resistant,

00:39:26.134 --> 00:39:28.300
like they don't want to get
up in front of everyone.

00:39:28.300 --> 00:39:29.341
But we like pull them up.

00:39:29.341 --> 00:39:31.489
But then they always end
up having a good time.

00:39:31.489 --> 00:39:33.530
I mean if someone I guess
if someone's resistant,

00:39:33.530 --> 00:39:36.840
we just back off and
go to the next person.

00:39:36.840 --> 00:39:39.480
DIANA: We often sometimes
will find out from a teacher.

00:39:39.480 --> 00:39:42.520
A teacher will tell us, please
have that child to come up.

00:39:42.520 --> 00:39:45.382
Or don't ask that
child to come up.

00:39:45.382 --> 00:39:46.840
So especially in
places where we're

00:39:46.840 --> 00:39:50.630
going back to where we
worked with them before.

00:39:50.630 --> 00:39:51.830
LEAH: Yes!

00:39:51.830 --> 00:39:52.790
More questions.

00:39:52.790 --> 00:39:53.517
I like questions.

00:39:53.517 --> 00:39:54.225
More interactive.

00:39:59.090 --> 00:40:28.500
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] some
situations just performing out

00:40:28.500 --> 00:40:43.640
there to make sure you're
going to stay safe.

00:40:48.960 --> 00:40:52.052
and whoever is
governing the area.

00:40:55.340 --> 00:40:55.840
LEAH: Yeah!

00:40:55.840 --> 00:40:57.735
Could I answer the first part.

00:41:00.570 --> 00:41:02.820
One thing I'll say, like I
said like at the beginning,

00:41:02.820 --> 00:41:05.430
I was like sometimes
people are a bit grumpy.

00:41:05.430 --> 00:41:08.290
So I definitely
been in places where

00:41:08.290 --> 00:41:11.090
there's like some of
the-- it seems to me

00:41:11.090 --> 00:41:14.740
like some of the guys in
charge like, hey what's this,

00:41:14.740 --> 00:41:15.250
you know?

00:41:15.250 --> 00:41:18.960
But I'll say that like once
we get people laughing,

00:41:18.960 --> 00:41:22.060
the mass majority just
seems to just like it

00:41:22.060 --> 00:41:24.950
right in like those
various I mean usually it's

00:41:24.950 --> 00:41:27.030
more received we were like, YAY.

00:41:27.030 --> 00:41:29.690
But in those occasions,
when something like that

00:41:29.690 --> 00:41:31.760
happens, once we kind
of get them laughing,

00:41:31.760 --> 00:41:33.800
and we just connect
with them, I think

00:41:33.800 --> 00:41:36.930
that those sort
of, I don't know,

00:41:36.930 --> 00:41:40.230
limitations or those
tensions, just fall away.

00:41:40.230 --> 00:41:42.090
They seem to just kind of go.

00:41:42.090 --> 00:41:43.550
And everyone kind
of like relaxes.

00:41:43.550 --> 00:41:46.070
And I think there's just
this general understanding,

00:41:46.070 --> 00:41:48.170
we're just here to
have a good time,

00:41:48.170 --> 00:41:50.190
and connect, and
make people laugh.

00:41:50.190 --> 00:41:56.820
And then I think it doesn't
feel imposing so much,

00:41:56.820 --> 00:42:01.214
as just sort of joining them
and an excuse for a good time.

00:42:01.214 --> 00:42:02.880
DIANA: So to answer
the safety question.

00:42:02.880 --> 00:42:05.400
We do put a lot of care
into the safety of things,

00:42:05.400 --> 00:42:08.502
and some of the folks
who work with us

00:42:08.502 --> 00:42:10.210
and who maybe aren't
the performer types,

00:42:10.210 --> 00:42:12.810
have worked for like
Doctors Without Borders,

00:42:12.810 --> 00:42:15.915
or we have a war
photographer who

00:42:15.915 --> 00:42:18.340
does a lot of the photography
for some of the shows,

00:42:18.340 --> 00:42:22.010
so we understand the precautions
that we have to take.

00:42:22.010 --> 00:42:29.090
When we're going into a really
fragile area or a new area like

00:42:29.090 --> 00:42:31.860
say Haiti right
after the earthquake.

00:42:31.860 --> 00:42:34.830
So we worked in Haiti
through very kind

00:42:34.830 --> 00:42:37.010
of informal connections
before the earthquake,

00:42:37.010 --> 00:42:39.400
and then after the
earthquake, we now only

00:42:39.400 --> 00:42:41.480
go there with a
strong connection

00:42:41.480 --> 00:42:43.031
to an organization
that invites us.

00:42:43.031 --> 00:42:45.030
And we get a safety
briefing before we go there.

00:42:45.030 --> 00:42:48.560
We have curfews, we really
don't have much freedom

00:42:48.560 --> 00:42:49.900
when we're traveling around.

00:42:49.900 --> 00:42:52.540
It's not like we're going
to eat in a fine dining

00:42:52.540 --> 00:42:54.070
hotel, or something like that.

00:42:54.070 --> 00:42:56.420
But we're actually
usually home and really

00:42:56.420 --> 00:42:59.950
exhausted and going to sleep
by 8 o'clock or 9 o'clock.

00:42:59.950 --> 00:43:04.120
So we're usually not out after
dark and things like that.

00:43:04.120 --> 00:43:07.750
If it's appropriate, were
escorted to a location.

00:43:07.750 --> 00:43:09.500
The parading through
houses, that actually

00:43:09.500 --> 00:43:11.930
was in Martissant,
and that happens often

00:43:11.930 --> 00:43:16.410
and that's because that's what
we were told was going to work.

00:43:16.410 --> 00:43:18.850
So we're asking local
people or people who

00:43:18.850 --> 00:43:21.980
have been living in the
communities for a long time,

00:43:21.980 --> 00:43:26.630
how do we promote
everyone to come to this?

00:43:26.630 --> 00:43:32.030
Or where is the most
appropriate space to perform,

00:43:32.030 --> 00:43:33.800
is another big one.

00:43:33.800 --> 00:43:36.230
Sometimes, I've been
on a couple trips

00:43:36.230 --> 00:43:39.080
where it's actually not safe
for our performers to perform.

00:43:39.080 --> 00:43:40.570
So that's something
we always try

00:43:40.570 --> 00:43:42.340
to have what we
call a logistician,

00:43:42.340 --> 00:43:45.010
or somebody like me who doesn't
need to be up there performing

00:43:45.010 --> 00:43:47.260
but is looking over the
clowns, making sure that their

00:43:47.260 --> 00:43:49.320
hydrated, making sure
that they're wearing close

00:43:49.320 --> 00:43:51.528
toed shoes, because a lot
of the places we perform in

00:43:51.528 --> 00:43:54.270
have glass all over the
ground, and things like that.

00:43:54.270 --> 00:43:57.760
So we take stock of
both the audience

00:43:57.760 --> 00:44:00.495
and being aware
of how much we're

00:44:00.495 --> 00:44:01.870
intruding on their
personal life,

00:44:01.870 --> 00:44:04.161
but we also have to make sure
that the clowns are safe,

00:44:04.161 --> 00:44:05.962
because they can't do
their work otherwise.

00:44:05.962 --> 00:44:08.462
ALEX: I just wanted to add, I
think that's a great question.

00:44:08.462 --> 00:44:12.392
And you do something willingly,
that you've done so many times

00:44:12.392 --> 00:44:13.642
that you forgot to explain it.

00:44:13.642 --> 00:44:17.720
And you break it down into all
these slices that you can use.

00:44:20.510 --> 00:44:23.685
So what clowns do, and
what anyone can do,

00:44:23.685 --> 00:44:27.030
is you go in there with
this joyful spirit,

00:44:27.030 --> 00:44:30.550
and present a little tiny thing.

00:44:30.550 --> 00:44:33.900
It could be just a little
gesture about a smile.

00:44:33.900 --> 00:44:36.426
But you put yourself out there.

